ion.org/60S3KqGCy?url=http://www.sacscoc.org/pdf/webmemlist.pdf |archive-date=July 25, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nThe Faulkner Eagles is the athletic name of the teams that compete for Faulkner University.  Faulkner participates in the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]]. Sports for men include baseball, basketball, football, golf and soccer. Sports for women include basketball, golf, soccer, softball and volleyball.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sports|url=http://www.faulknereagles.com/}}</ref> Most sports participate within the [[Southern States Athletic Conference]], while football participates in the [[Mid-South Conference]]'s sun division, starting with the 2016 season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilson|first1=Michael|title=Local teams officially join Mid-South football conference |url=http://www.theledger.com/article/20160225/SPORTS19/160229601|accessdate=27 February 2016|publisher=The Lakeland Ledger|date=25 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Members|url=http://thesunconference.com/sports/2012/7/2/members.aspx|website=Thesunconference.com|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> Faulkner formerly also competed in the [[NCCAA]], winning the national championship in baseball in 2001.<ref name=\"Barker Leaves\">{{cite news|title=Faulkner announces resignation of football coach, athletic director Brent Barker|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/06/faulkner_announces_resignation.html|accessdate=20 February 2017|date=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni and faculty==\n;Alumni\n*[[Bobby Bright]] {{en dash}} United States Congressman from Alabama<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B001264|title=BRIGHT, Bobby Neal, Sr., (1952 \u2013 )|publisher= Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate= February 2, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Marcus Brimage]] {{en dash}} professional [[Mixed Martial Artist]], former [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] competitor<ref>{{cite web|title=Marcus Brimage UFC Profile|url=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Marcus-Brimage|archiveurl=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/marcus-Brimage|archivedate=July 16, 2017|publisher=[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]}}</ref>\n*[[Beau Torbert]] Baseball, Drafted by the Houston Astros in 2004. Sioux Falls Canaries Hall of Fame. Baseball America Independent Player of the Year 2010\n*[[Corey Black]] Baseball, Chicago Cubs\n*[[Ray Ray Armstrong]] Football, New York Giants\n*Tim Ragland - Mayor of Talladega, Alabama\n\n;Faculty\n*[[Allison Garrett]] {{en dash}} Associate Professor of Law (2004{{en dash}}07)\n*[[Michael A. O'Donnell]] {{en dash}} Assistant Professor of Family Studies, Dean of Professional Studies\n\n==Graduate programs==\n===Law===\nFaulkner operates the [[Thomas Goode Jones School of Law]], with between 200 and 300 students.<ref>{{cite web|title=Faulkner University, Thomas Goode Jones School of Law |url=http://www.nationaljurist.com/law-schools/faulkner-university-thomas-goode-jones-school-law|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325054815/http://www.nationaljurist.com/law-schools/faulkner-university-thomas-goode-jones-school-law|archivedate=March 25, 2017|work=National Jurist}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Zaretsky|first1=Staci|title=Lafayette Movie Theater Gunman Was A Law School Graduate|url=http://abovethelaw.com/2015/07/lafayette-movie-theater-gunman-was-a-law-school-graduate/|date=July 24, 2015|publisher=[[Above the Law (website)|Above the Law]]}}</ref> The school of law was provisionally accredited by the American Bar Association in 2006, and fully accredited in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Faulkner University, Thomas Goode Jones School of Law|url=http://www.lsac.org/officialguide/2013/lsac_1331.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817124557/http://www.lsac.org/officialguide/2013/lsac_1331.asp|archivedate=August 17, 2016|publisher=Law School Admission Council}}</ref>\n\n===Theology===\nThe Kearley Graduate School of Theology, which opened the fall of 2013, offers students Masters of Arts degrees in Biblical Theology,<ref>{{cite web|title=Faulkner University Forms New Graduate School of Theology, Honors F. Furman Kearley|author=Matheny, J. Randal|url=http://brotherhoodnews.com/2013/04/26/faulkner-university-graduate-school-theology/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710082905/http://brotherhoodnews.com/2013/04/26/faulkner-university-graduate-school-theology/|archivedate=July 10, 2017|publisher=Brotherhood News}}</ref> as well as a [[Low-residency program|low-residency]] PhD in Biblical Studies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Faulkner University|url=http://www.educationcorner.com/colleges/alabama/faulkner-university-alabama.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202000757/http://www.educationcorner.com/colleges/alabama/faulkner-university-alabama.html|archivedate=February 2, 2017|publisher=Education Corner}}</ref>\n\n===Humanities===\nFaulkner University is one of a handful of high-learning institutions in the United States that still teaches from the canon of literature known as the Great Books of the Western World. Students attending Faulkner University are able to obtain a low-residency Master's degree or a PhD in the Humanities through the university\u2019s Honors College.<ref>{{cite web|title=Master of Arts in Humanities|url=https://www.faulkner.edu/online/academics/master-arts-humanities/|publisher=Faulkner University|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707193844/https://www.faulkner.edu/online/academics/master-arts-humanities/|archivedate=July 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Doctor of Philosophy in Humanities|url=https://www.faulkner.edu/online/academics/doctor-philosophy-humanities/|publisher=Faulkner University|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108012853/https://www.faulkner.edu/online/academics/doctor-philosophy-humanities/|archive-date=November 8, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Amridge University]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n